    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>World Briefing | Europe: It Just Rained a Lot</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Andrew C. Revkin (NYT)</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Revkin, Andrew C</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>German researchers, reporting in journal Nature, find no link between extreme flooding of Oder and Elbe rivers and theory of global warming; contend data as far back as 1021 shows decrease in flood frequency, despite record flooding in Prague and Dresden in past few years (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Last summer, many officials and residents were ascribing the severe flooding in Dresden and Prague and other parts of Europe to global warming and its effect on storm patterns. But a new study of the Oder and Elbe rivers, both of which have produced record floods in recent years, shows an overall decline in the frequency of floods, German researchers are reporting in the journal Nature. The scientists went as far back as 1021 and said they found no trend in big summer floods and a downward trend in extreme winter floods.</p>
        <p>Andrew C. Revkin (NYT)</p>
      </block>
